// Fick
"Fick.title" = "Fick Optical Illusion";
"Fick.description" = "The Fick illusion was proposed by Fick in 1851, in which figures of the same length appear to be longer than those of the same length when they are aligned vertically or horizontally. The two figures \"A\" and \"B\" in the right image are congruent, but B appears to be longer than A. In addition, A appears to be thicker than B. In addition, figure A appears to be thicker than figure B. This is generally believed to be caused by the fact that vertical-horizontal lines are perceived to be longer than horizontal lines, but the detailed mechanism has not yet been clarified because figure B appears to be longer than figure A even when the figure is tilted 90 degrees. This illusion is also called the vertical-horizontal illusion (V-H illusion).";
